(5, 5, 'facebook', '1287782553_10200636372733573', 'b2e0953626037bf944f66d22c51bd1d9', 'Thursday. 19th September. Taputaputa Bay.\r\n\r\nApparently itâ€™s â€œInternational â€˜Talk like a pirateâ€™ Dayâ€ â€¦ arrrr Jim ladâ€¦ me heartiesâ€¦. Yo ho-ho... and all that.\r\n\r\nI like this place. The surf has a proper West Coast rumble about it. I checked the compass, and no, this beach actually faced north, but I still think of it as a Westie beach.\r\n\r\nThe campsite is on a riverbank with one side river, one side beach and two sides steep bush. The river bit is tidalâ€¦ likeâ€¦ wellâ€¦ the beach (but not the bush). The river comes down a steep and narrow valley, which funnelled wind through the campsite all night. There is a contest between the cliffs and the valley to determine the wind direction over the campsite, and it kept flicking from one side of the van to the other all night. I had to get up in the night and lower the satellite dish as it was wrenching around in the gusts and making some very expensive noises.\r\n\r\nLast night I watched â€˜Nothing Trivialâ€™ on TV. It was odd watching it and knowing that I wasnâ€™t there this season. None of the extraâ€™s I usually hang around with were in it either; I guess they wanted younger faces in the quiz teams this year. It was also a little odd having the only TV in the place. For some reason I felt a bit shy about winding the dish up, but I''d got over it by the time the News and Weather came on.\r\n\r\nAfter dark there were more arrivals; cars and more â€˜al frescoâ€™ campervans. I was glad I hadnâ€™t left it until dark. It would have been difficult finding anywhere approaching level, and this place has quite a few soft spots. The small vans that came in will probably be OK, but I''d seen the wheel marks Iâ€™d made while levelling up I noticed that Iâ€™d had a small wheel spin at one stage. The gearing on this thing is so low that I hadnâ€™t even noticed it. However, it pinpointed a soft spot that I wonâ€™t go over again.\r\n\r\nI really donâ€™t understand the people in these little vans. When I arrived, folk were already getting ready for bed. They were fully closed up and dark by 7:00. This morning, Iâ€™d been up three hours. Iâ€™d breakfasted, shaved, showered, and watched the first race of the Americaâ€™s Cup... and still six of the vans were dormant and curtained.\r\n\r\nThe forecast for today had been a little optimistic. The morning brought ain and a big blow. No six hour walk today, it would have been miserable, so I decided that Iâ€™d watch the Americaâ€™s Cup races and then move around to Spirits Bay. \r\n\r\nThe light wasnâ€™t very kind but I took some pictures anyway. It was overcast and gloomy, so the photoâ€™s donâ€™t let make place very appealing; it deserves better. It would be a really lovely spot in the summer, but then I suspect it will always be crowded during peak season as itâ€™s just 10 minutes from Cape Reinga.\r\n\r\nAs I did the last of my washing up in lovely hot soapy water, I looked across at my nearest neighbours, compressed into their tiny van, trying to have breakfast without elbowing each other in the ear. I packed up with some care. \r\n\r\nThe road into Taputaputa was straightforward enough, but I expected a bit more from the track into Spirits Bay, so I took some care packing. It was 15km of dirt road, leading to nowhere except a little used campground. Iâ€™d memorised the directions... first left, then first left. The 30km should take about 90 minutes.\r\n\r\nI was about right with the time, though my assumption about the road was unduly pessimistic, it was just fine; you could have driven a tour bus down it (or maybe not). \r\n\r\nTaputaputa Bay campsite\r\nhttp://goo.gl/maps/wD0tM\r\n\r\nTaputaputa Bay to Spirits Bay.\r\nhttp://goo.gl/maps/SdQhb\r\n\r\nSpirits Bay campsite\r\nhttp://goo.gl/maps/E590o\r\n\r\n(A little side note here. When I give a â€˜Google Mapsâ€™ link to a campsite, the green arrow indicates the precise position that I parked)\r\n\r\nAt Spirits Bay I had a good walk around, seeing what I needed to see, and exploring what took my fancy. I was looking for a way to cross the river to get eastwards but couldnâ€™t find one. There was a footpath shown on the map, and I was hoping for a little bridge, but no such luck. It was too deep to walk through. Even in a four wheel drive it looked like a mission. However, once on the beach I found that I could easily walk through it. Like at Piha and Bethells, what looked like a formidable obstacle inland was a mere trickle at the waterâ€™s edge. \r\n\r\nI crossed. It was a â€˜one footâ€™ stream. The number denotes the width of the stream. The width of the stream in metres is; one, plus the number of wet feet you have.\r\n\r\nFrom the other side of the stream I could walk up to a ridge that leads to the cliff top. I might not be able to get all the way to Tom Bowling Bay and back without a herculean effort, but I would be able to get far enough along to get a good view into it. That would be enough for my purposes.\r\n\r\nSpirits Bay was giving me some grief, and a real problemâ€¦ wind. Parked up I was listing about 10 degrees in the strong gusts. The roof vents were flexing and twisting open, and the satellite dish, even lowered, was straining on its fastenings. I couldnâ€™t stay there unless I either found shelter, or the wind dropped. In my walk around I hadnâ€™t found any shelter. The wind was straight from the north, off the sea, which meant where Iâ€™d come from was getting it too. My choices were limited and I had to make a decision.\r\n\r\nI chose bacon. \r\n\r\nThereâ€™s nothing quite so cheering on a gloomy day as bacon sandwiches and a steaming hot mug of tea. \r\n\r\nAfter a combined dose of; protein, fat, salt, sugar and caffeine considered lethal by the most health practitioners I decided to move. Before I left I wrote â€œspatula & non-stick frying panâ€ on the whiteboard.\r\n\r\nThe road out of Spirits Bay seemed a lot more rutted than I remembered on the way inâ€¦ and it actually was. It took me a while to figure out why the side I was now travelling on was so much rougher than the other side. The answer was the forestry block out by Spirits Bay. The logging trucks arrive empty, but they leave fully loaded. Thus, they damage one side of the road more than the other. The rattling and shaking was incredible, and I feared for the well-being of my beautiful monitor. A couple more kilometres further on I figured out a solution, and completed the remainder of that leg on the wrong side of the road.\r\n\r\nPast Waitiki Landing again and heading south I picked out a couple more landmarks that I needed to find. There were a couple of beach access points that were important to me. The track to the coast from Te Paki stream comes out on the beach level with Tasmanâ€™s noon position on Jan 3rd. The end of Te Ahu Road is where he was at sunrise that morning when he first saw Cape Maria van Diemenâ€¦ two more ticks on the list. \r\n\r\nI needed to be out of the rain but more importantly the wind. There was a DOC campsite halfway down the Peninsula at Rarawa Beach. There arenâ€™t that many choices out on the peninsula and I needed to check what my options would be for when I next came, so I pulled off the main road and straight onto another dirt track. This track was like a motorway by comparison. It was wide, straight and flat, and I hurtled along only disappointed that I wasnâ€™t leaving a grand plume of rising behind, parading my progress. All I was leaving today was tyre tracks in wet cow pats.\r\n\r\nI found an excellent sheltered spot; in the lee of a hill and behind a row of trees. It was calm in there and level. I needed to see no more, pulled up the handbrake, and put up my feet. I was tired. Iâ€™d had an uneasy sleep last night what with all the bouncing around the van was doing.\r\n\r\nRarawa campsite\r\n-34.726183,173.083634\r\nhttp://goo.gl/maps/oFx9n\r\n\r\nSpirits Bay to Rarawa\r\nhttp://goo.gl/maps/lWnwf\r\n\r\nAfter a quick siesta, I worked for a while writing the history of the Dutch East India Company as compactly and concisely as I was able. Itâ€™s not particularly exciting, but itâ€™s essential to understanding some aspects of Tasmanâ€™s journey, so thereâ€™s no way to avoid it. The best I can do is keep it brief and lightâ€¦after all, I donâ€™t want the punters falling asleep before they get to the good bits do I?\r\n\r\nFor a leg stretcher I thought I should visit the beach, after all, I was at one. Pulling my coat on I strode manfully through the trees to the dune crest. I poked my head over the parapet long enough to snap two shots and immediately sounded the retreat. It was still raining a gale out there and Iâ€™d had quite enough of that for one day.\r\n\r\nThe TV weatherman told me that tomorrow would bring rain with possible thunder in the afternoon. That clinched it, I was moving off the cape. I had another pressing reason to move on too. While I had taken every care to ensure I was properly provisioned for the trip, I hadnâ€™t bothered to check my wardrobe. I was wearing my last clean shirt, and only had two pairs of clean socks left. My laundry bag was full, all my fleeces were damp and things were starting to get pretty smelly.\r\n\r\nIn the morning Iâ€™d go to Kaitaia. Kaitaia had a laundrette, and launderettes have both washing machinesâ€¦ and dryers!\r\n\r\nI went happily to bed with the roar of surf in my ears, and the scent of bacon up my nose.', 'EN', NULL, 'https://www.facebook.com/1287782553_10200636372733573', 'link', NULL, 'http://external.ak.fbcdn.net/safe_image.php?d=AQCmcPFTlhDdS7io&w=154&h=154&url=https%3A%2F%2Fkhms0.google.co.nz%2Fkh%2Fv%3D137%26src%3Dapp%26cookie%3Dfzwq1PfqVkaDPMUX2ZwTLU0zwBV89hdEKkTr-A%26x%3D128420%26s%3D%26y%3D78905%26z%3D17%26s%3DGalil', 'http://goo.gl/maps/wD0tM', '-34.437292,172.71629 - Google Maps', 'maps.google.co.nz', 'View maps and find local businesses on the web.', NULL, NULL, 'Dave Horry'